Date: Wed 24 Jul 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@vet.gla.ac.uk>
Source: Taiwan News, via Newsline, Tue 23 Jul 2002 [edited]

Taiwan: Dengue Fever Outbreak Affects Kaohsiung and Kaohsiung
County
--------------------------------------------------------------------
The Greater Kaohsiung Area in southern Taiwan is suffering from its
most serious dengue fever threat in 14 years, with 383 people having
been infected by the mosquito-borne disease so far this year [2002] as
of yesterday.
Of the 383 reported cases, 10 involve the more fatal dengue
hemorrhagic fever, the Department of Health (DOH) reported
yesterday. All of the cases have been confirmed as having originated in
Taiwan, according to the DOH's Center for Disease Control.
A total of 384 cases of the disease have been reported island-wide, with
262 cases in the port city of Kaohsiung and 121 cases in Kaohsiung
County; one case has been reported in Taipei County in northern
Taiwan.
The DOH warned last week of a possible outbreak of dengue fever in
southern Taiwan, with the number of reported cases of the tropical
disease increasing by about 10 per day. The Health authority also
warned tourists bound for southeast Asia of an outbreak of dengue
fever currently rampant in Malaysia [see [2] below].
In Taipei City, despite the fact that there hasn't been a single case of
dengue fever reported, health officials have put some districts on red
alert against a possible outbreak as the density of the mosquito
population has reached as high as Level 4, meaning 20-34 mosquitoes
or mosquito larvae found in every 100 households. These districts
include Ta-an and Chungcheng districts. Health officials issue dengue
fever warnings when the mosquito density reaches Level 2, 5-9
mosquitoes or larvae found in every 100 households.
Taipei Health Department officials have urged city residents to undergo
a medical checkup if they have traveled to Southeast Asia or southern
Taiwan over the past 2 weeks and have developed symptoms such as a
sudden high fever, severe headaches, nausea, vomiting, or muscle and
joint pains. As of 4 years ago, almost all the reported cases of dengue
fever in Taiwan, including cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever, were
found to have originated from abroad, brought in by returning visitors
to Thailand and other Southeast Asian countries.
