[2]
Date: Wed 24 Jul 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@vet.gla.ac.uk>
Source: New Straits Times (Malaysia), Tue 23 Jul 2002 [edited]

Matalysia: Perak Put on Dengue Fever Alert
------------------------------------------
Perak has been put on dengue alert after the vector-borne disease
claimed 6 lives in the last 6 months, including that of a 7-month-old
baby boy from Simpang, Taiping. The others, aged between 20 and 52
years, were from Ipoh (2 victims), Batu Kurau (one), Kuala Kangsar
(one) and Bidor (one). While 5 of the deaths occurred last month [June
2002], the other was in May.
State Health and Environment Committee chairman Datuk Ho Cheng
Wang said today all district hospitals and health departments had been
ordered to monitor the situation and report new cases to the State
Government, especially the deadly dengue haemorrhagic fever. He said
private hospitals and clinics had also been informed of the situation
and had promised to cooperate to prevent the spread of the disease.
He said from January 2002 to June 2002, there were 1089 dengue and
dengue haemorrhagic fever cases, of which 184 were reported in June
2002. Ho said in the first 6 months of last year [2001], there were only
637 dengue cases -- and only one death for the whole of last year. He
said Kuala Kangsar was the worst hit with 250 cases, followed by
Manjung (179), Ipoh (167), Kinta (103) and Hilir Perak (102). He said
preventive measures had been taken, including fogging and anti-
dengue campaigns.
