Date: Wed 24 Jul 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@vet.gla.ac.uk>
Source: BBC International Reports, Tue 23 Jul 2002
(Text of report by Caribbean Media Corporation (CMC) news agency,
Mon 22 Jul 2002) [edited]

Trinidad: Extent of Dengue Outbreak in Dispute
----------------------------------------------
The Trinidad and Tobago government has denied an outbreak of
dengue fever in the country, even as Health Minister Colm Imbert
announced plans to deal with _Aedes aegypti _ mosquitoes, the carriers
of the disease. Imbert told reporters that while his ministry was aware
of some cases of dengue fever, the situation could not be characterized
as an outbreak. "I would not say there is a crisis, what I would say is
there is a problem," Imbert told reporters, adding that, "there is a
problem between reported and confirmed cases of dengue."
But the Health Ministry has taken out newspaper advertisements
outlining measures to be adopted by residents to deal with the situation.
The advertisements also warn that persons found guilty of breeding
[sic] _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes could be charged 480 Trinidad and
Tobago dollars (80 US dollars). "Together we can do something about
dengue," the advertisement says, informing residents to clear their
property of tins, tires and unused containers that were "favourite sites
for mosquitoes".
Newspaper reports said that at least one person was "battling for his
life, while there are some 30 patients" at the San Fernando Hospital.
The reports said that the man was suffering from dengue haemorrhagic
fever that could result in death. On Mon 22 Jul 2002, Dr Austin
Trinidade, chief of staff at the hospital, was quoted in a local
newspaper as saying that a number of people had been coming to the
hospital suffering from "dengue-type symptoms".
