Honduras: National Emergency Declared
-------------------------------------
Honduras President Ricardo Maduro has declared a national emergency
due to the country's dengue epidemic, when announcing the measures
the government will implement to fight the disease. The President
announced on national television that the immediate priority is to
control the outburst of dengue, particularly in the main urban centers
of Tegucigalpa and San Pedro Sula, to prevent the spread of the
disease to other cities, and make sure that the impact of the control is
sustainable and thus avoid more deaths.
This week, 242 cases of dengue haemorrhagic fever were confirmed,
and another 423 people are suspected of suffering the illness. The
Metropolitan Area continues to report 64 percent of the total number of
cases. So far 9 deaths are confirmed and a further 12 are suspected of
dying of dengue. Hospital Escuela, which is the most important public
hospital in Tegucigalpa, is saturated and there is no space left.
Control will only be achieved through a massive fumigation campaign
and actions to avoid the growth of the larvae of the mosquito
transmitting the disease. A fumigation campaign has been ordered with
chemicals that do not affect the health of the people, but are effective
against the mosquito.
"My commitment is to do everything possible to avoid dengue taking
more lives. Therefore, to combat the crisis, together with my cabinet,
we have declared a national emergency to fight against dengue: we will
allocate US$1.2 million to reinforce the program that is being
executed," said the President.
Permanent Cleaning Committees have been formed to get rid of all
materials that could be a breeding place for the mosquito, and are being
trained in the application of Untadita, a mix of detergent and chlorine
that helps to eliminate the larvae of the mosquito in washing basins and
other recipients, instructing to clean these washing basins every 7 days.
In his speech, the President thanked the international community for its
support in the fight against the epidemic highlighting the participation
of US-AID, and the governments of Sweden, Cuba, Guatemala and
Mexico.
