[6]
Date: Thu 25 Jul 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Agence France Press, Wed 24 Jul 2002 [edited]

Bangladesh: Dengue Fever Returns to Dhaka
-----------------------------------------
Dengue fever has returned to the Bangladeshi capital Dhaka, killing 7
people so far this month and affecting some 200 others, senior health
official Kanak Ranjan Talukder said on Wed 24 Jul 2002. At least 6
people died of the infection in Dhaka's leading diabetic hospital, where
5 to 6 dengue patients have been admitted daily since 1 Jul 2002,
Talukder told Agence France Press.
A 10-year-old boy died in the nearby Dhaka Medical College Hospital,
where about 4 people are being admitted daily suffering from fever.
Health Ministry officials said municipal health squads were taking
preventive measures to contain the infection, which is spread by
mosquitoes. Characterised by painful joints, fever and a rash, dengue
symptoms usually begin within a week of a mosquito's bite and last for
7 days.
An outbreak of dengue fever in Bangladesh last year [2001] claimed
more than 44 lives, Talukder said. In October 2000, Bangladesh began
a 5-year action plan to contain dengue fever after 3837 people became
infected, 70 of whom died.
The World Health Organisation earlier expressed concern about a
dengue fever outbreak in southeast Asia and the south Pacific which
last year [2001] left more than 340 people dead.
