Date: Fri 26 Jul 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters News Service, Fri 26 Jul 2002 [edited]

El Salvador Declares National Emergency over Dengue Fever
---------------------------------------------------------
El Salvador declared a national emergency on Fri 26 Jul 2002 to battle a
dengue epidemic that so far has claimed 9 lives since January 2002 in
the Central American nation. Health authorities said El Salvador has
seen 3203 cases of dengue fever this year [2002], 206 of them the
potentially lethal dengue hemorrhagic fever. There have also been 14
000 suspected cases.
Dengue is transmitted by mosquitoes and the national emergency,
approved by a majority of legislators in Congress, enables the
government to free up more funds to fight the epidemic. It also means
the emergency will be led by the Defense Ministry in coordination with
the Health Ministry, adding weight to the fight to contain the epidemic.
"We continue to have high levels of (mosquito) larvae which expose us
to an expansion of the epidemic," Deputy Health Minister Herbert
Betancourt told reporters after the emergency was approved.
Dengue epidemics have also broken out in neighboring Honduras and
Guatemala. The 3 countries are trying to cobble together a long-term
regional plan to fight the disease. Honduras, where dengue fever has
killed a dozen people, mostly children, declared a similar national
emergency on Mon 22 Jul 2002.
