[8]
Date: Sun 28 Jul 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Fuente elsalvador.com, Fri 26 Jul 2002
<http://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/2002/7/26/nacional/nacio20.html>
(translated by Mod.JT) [edited]

El Salvador: Appearance of Dengue Virus Type 3
----------------------------------------------
The persistence of dengue transmission and the appearance of a new
serotype of the virus [for the country], dengue virus type 3 (DEN-3),
has forced the Salvadorian National Assembly to declare a state of
emergency throughout the whole the country yesterday. Whereas only a
month ago the reported national incidence was 16 cases per day, it is
now 30 cases per day. On 30 Jun 2002, the National Assembly had
already declared a state of emergency in the Departments of San
Salvador, Santa Ana, La Libertad, and Cabanas, as well as in any other
zone where cases of dengue, either classic or hemorrhagic, have been
detected.
The situation is complicated by the presence of the serotype DEN-3,
said the Minister of Health, Jose Lopez Beltran, yesterday during the
presentation of his annual review of activities to the Assembly. Lopez
Beltran requested extension of the state of emergency, after meeting last
weekend in Esquipulas, Guatemala, Ministers of Health Mario Bolanos,
of Guatemala, and Elias Lizardo, of Honduras, to analyze the situation
of dengue in the region. At this meeting the presence of DEN-3 in El
Salvador was acknowledged, as well as the fact that dengue fever is not
a local but is a hemispheric problem.
[The reintroduction of DEN-3 to Central America, where it has been
absent for about 20 years, was reported in 1994. The same serotype
was isolated a few months later in Nicaragua, Panama, Costa Rica,
Guatemala, El Salvador, and Honduras. The accumulation of a large
young population not previously exposed to this serotype of dengue
virus, living in conditions favorable to the transmission of the
infection, facilitates the potential occurrence of massive outbreaks of
the infection and the appearance of dengue hemorrhagic fever. For
these reasons, the steady increase in the incidence of the disease in the
region comes as no surprise.
Viral envelope gene sequence data from DEN-3 isolates from Panama
and Nicaragua have shown that this new American DEN-3 strain is
likely a recent introduction from Asia, since it is genetically distinct
from the DEN-3 strain found previously in the Americas, but is
identical to the DEN-3 strain that caused major outbreaks of dengue
hemorrhagic fever in Sri Lanka and India in the 1980s. - Mod.JT]
